14 April 2016

Background

  • The S&P 500 is a widely followed equity index and benchmarks in the US
  • There are many ways to trade the S&P
  • Futures, options and other derivatives
  • Exchange traded funds (e.g. SPY)
  • Investment funds
  • Those different markets publish public information about various investors' positions
  • Can we use this information and various forecasting models to predict future returns and create profits better than through simple models?

Overview of the dataset

Which data will we use?

  • Price information: Price and volume of the SPDR ETF (SPY)
  • CBOE Index put and call volume - volume of put and call options traded on equity indices (more call options = bullish, put options = bearish)
  • Commitment of trader report (COT) - Every week reports number of long and short future contracts held by:
  • Large speculators - investment funds and hedge funds ('smart money')
  • Commercials - investment banks, brokers and market makers
  • Others - Speculators below the reporting threshold
  • The weekly change in investors' net positions could hold clues as to future market direction

How do variables evolve over time?

  • 2008 crash and subsequent recovery evident in the chart
  • No obvious linear correlation between different SPY price and non-price variables
  • Price series is non-stationary so we will look at predicting returns

What do S&P500 returns between 2006 and 2016 look like?

  • Mean and median slightly positive but close to 0%
  • Fat tails evident:
  • Extreme of c.-20% once
  • A few occurences >10%
  • Simple benchmark would be to assume returns equal to mean returns

Overview of the models

Forecasting and comparison methodology

  • The models are trained on a training set, between November 2006 and November 2012
  • The fitted models are then used to forecast weekly returns in a test period from the end of the training period to March 2016
  • Difference between predicted and actual returns in the forecast period allows us to gauge accuracy
  • We can compare the models by looking at their root mean squared errors - RMSE (the square root of the average deviation between fitted values and actual values) in the test period
  • The lower the RMSE in the test period, the better the fit

Models tested

  • We'll look at the following algorithms:
  • Benchmark model 1 - returns equal mean returns
  • Benmark model 2 - returns equal the most recent returns
  • Multiple linear regression
  • Regression trees

  • Random forest

  • The models were chosen due to their ability to take into account multiple variables and to find non-linear relationships

Benchmark models

Models to beat

Benchmark model 1 - Average approach

  • The average approach predicts that all future returns equal the mean return of the training set (+0.08%)
  • Given the distribution of returns, this could be a reasonably good prediction of future returns
  • The chart shows a good fit both in the training and test periods
  • The RMSE in the test period for the average approach is c.1.69

Benchmark model 2 - Naive approach

  • The naive approach simply assumes that returns at time t+1 equal current returns at time t
  • If changes in returns are persistent, this could be a good approximation
  • The RMSE for the naive approach in the test period is c.2.5, and the chart shows the fit is not particularly good

Models to test

Linear Regression

  • The linear regression model attempts to find a relationship between returns and the various non-price variables (in addition to the previous week's returns)
  • The results of the regression suggested that only the following variables were important: Previous % return, change in net put colume, and the change in the put-call ratio so only those variables were kept
  • However, the multiple R^2 for the equation is only c.1.97%, suggesting that the variables chosen do not explain much of the variation in returns
  • The RMSE for multiple linear regression in the test period is c.1.8, better than the naive but worse than the average approach

Regression Tree

  • The regression tree model creates a decision tree which fits the training set subject to a complexity parameter (which can be adjusted order to avoid overfitting) that determines the number of nodes for the decision tree
  • The complexity parameter suggested by the model as minimising cross-validated error is none, and would yield the average model. However, to see whether choosing a tree with five splits is better than the naive model
  • The following shows the decision tree model fitted to the training set

Regression Tree - cont.

  • The RMSE for the regression tree model is c.1.95, which is worse than all but the naive approach

Random Forest

  • The random forest algorithm creates a large number of decision trees and chooses the mean predicted return from those individual trees to improve accuracy vs. a standard regression tree and improving the latter's tendency towards overfitting
  • The random forest algorithm was run with 5,000 trees
  • The following chart shows the different features' importance according to the algorithm:

Random Forest - cont.

  • The RMSE for the random forest algorithm is c1.88, which is better than the regression tree algorithm but does not improve on the other models

Model Comparison

Root mean squared errors by model

  • The worst model is clearly the naive approach
  • The linear model is more accurate than all but the average approach
  • This would suggest overfitting in the other models, with complexity not improving results

Graphical representation of residuals

Accuracy in prediction of correct direction of price move

  • Save for the average approach, the accuracy of price direction prediction is not significantly different from random
  • Nevertheless, magnitude when correct is also important
  • Looking at the algorithms again with a binary approach (positive or negative price change) could yield interesting results

Conclusion

  • There is limited evidence that the non-price variables are helpful with the algorithms used to gain an edge in predicting prices versus a simple average approach

  • Overfitting is an issue, and doing further work with more data (perhaps on a lower timeframe) may improve the results

  • We can however draw useful conclusions from the analysis performed:
  • The distribution of returns suggests that a mean-reverting trading strategy on SPY intra-week may work as weekly returns tend towards slightly above zero. Thus any intra-week deviation do not tend to last according to the distribution
  • The price chart suggests that on higher timeframes there are clear trends where a trend-following approach may be work well

  • Complex models without sufficient data or features that explain the dependent variable well do not trump simple approaches

Suggested Next Steps

  • Review lower timeframes to test whether intra-week mean reversion approach has profit potential (taking into account trading costs)
  • Perform analysis on higher timeframe to see whether variables have longer-term prediction power and whether long-term returns would father other types of trading strategies
  • Develop a complete backtesting system that integrates code from the models developed to test profitability
  • Look at more sophisticated algorithms, such as neural networks
